Here&#39;s what will happen when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates
Interest rates will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
This we know.
What we don&#39;t know is how soon it will happen and how long it will last.
In economics, history offers little indication of timing.
After the first interest rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve&#39;s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That&#39;s why U.S. central bank officials have emphasized so strongly that investors should focus not on when interest rates start to rise, but on the trajectory of how long it will take for normalization.
Indeed, there are multiple variables at play.
But in the end, market players may find that all the interest rate hike hype has been overblown.
&quot;The Fed&#39;s first interest rate hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the &#39;cheap money&#39; era,&quot; Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
Conversely, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock that everyone seems to fear.
But it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Here&#39;s how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has been dealing with in recent months, the prospect of a rate hike may volatilize things for a while.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
&quot;There appears to be a tendency for returns on equity to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, perhaps again reflecting the misphasing in monetary policy,&quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what will happen after Fed hikes.
Specifically, over the past 35 years, the market has risen sharply - by about 14 percent - heading into rising interest rates, fairly invariant in the 250-day period following (2.6% average rise) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron&#39;s by Nuveen Asset Management&#39;s chief strategist.
Deutsche said the impact on equities tends to become more pronounced later in the cycle of interest rate hikes and benefits start to wane.
Recession is a fact of economic life but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, gross domestic product will approach its all-time low for a Fed rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice has nominal GDP been less than 4.5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few expect that to persist, with the third quarter reaching just 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and raise the question &quot;whether this time is different,&quot; Deutsche said.
Market players have been bracing all year for a hike decision from the Fed, with all eyes on this week&#39;s Federal Open Market Commission meeting, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an interest rate hike at this meeting, futures trades indicate a probability of just 25%.
&quot;In our post-1950 study, all interest rate hike cycles to date have been in a super cycle of profit growth, with GDP eclipsing pre-recession peaks very quickly after the recovery began,&quot; the report said.
On the contrary, this was an oddly slow recovery from the worst recession of the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has expected since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and this one has reached 74 months and counting.
Fixed income has also been volatile given that the market anticipates a rise in interest rates and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for stocks when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, the benefits seem to change direction as soon as the first up/down in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate hike cycle, bond yields fall immediately,” Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe these rate hikes will cause short-term and long-term bond yields to converge, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds are doing better in such an environment, although &quot;we&#39;re still cautious about yield forcing,&quot; Kathy Jones, fixed income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes markets have already adjusted to Fed policy expectations.
&quot;In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in expected inflation, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,&quot; Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, the spread of the average credit interest rate has widened and volatility has increased - all characteristics of the market when the Fed tightens policy.
Broadly speaking, companies operating mostly in the US will benefit from the rise in interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with high debts will suffer because the rise of the dollar will make their products more expensive in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
&quot;History shows that &#39;quality&#39; stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate hike,&quot; Goldman Sachs analysts said in a note to clients.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with weak balance sheets after each of the 1994, 1999, and 2004 interest rate hikes by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with both high equity returns and low-volatility stocks also outperformed peers with lower quality by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points), respectively.
Debt will become a major issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the dollar&#39;s rise.
Savers could also benefit, although experts disagree on how quickly that will happen.
