Advantages and disadvantages of converting credits into Swiss francs
Two offers have already appeared on the banking market to convert loans in Swiss francs into lei, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
The disadvantages can come in a few years, when the variable interest rate can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just finished the process regarding the conversion of loans in francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its own customers.
According to the data collected by the analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest in lei, of 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Banca Transilvania&#39;s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced by the value of the risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5% on the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own clients, compared to the equivalent monthly payment in lei before the conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5%, and Bancpost, by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
BENEFITS
The main advantage of covering loans in CHF in lei is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases in the franc, and the loan repayment will be made in the currency in which the salary is received.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no revaluation of the property, no additional guarantees are required and no further proof of income.
Practically, a new financial and legal analysis of the loan will not be made, nor will there be additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount on the monthly rate, compared to what customers paid before the conversion, equivalent in lei.
risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years consists mostly of interest, and the client repays very little of the principal.
Bancpost&#39;s offer with very low interest in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
However, it is not known how this interest will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be higher than 3.25%, so overall, the cost reduction is also lower.
A possible risk for all loans in lei with variable interest is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor - CHF index).
For example, three-month ROBOR is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it reached 6%, in 2009, at over 15%, and in a few days of 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs may appear, not mentioned in the initial offer.
