PHE published the &quot;landmark&quot; report last month and described it as a &quot;comprehensive analysis of the evidence.&quot;
But several researchers questioned the robustness of the data and pointed to links between certain experts and the tobacco industry.
An article published last month in the Lancet medical journal attacked the &quot;extraordinarily flimsy basis&quot; on which PHE based its main conclusion.
Two other researchers writing in the BMJ questioned the claims and their substantiation &quot;on solid ground or quicksand&quot;.
Martin McKee, professor of European public health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, professor of clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: &quot;A fundamental principle of public health is that policies must be based on evidence of effectiveness.&quot;
They said they expected PHE&#39;s claims that &quot;current estimates show that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking&quot; to be substantiated by a detailed analysis of evidence and models.
In fact, a single meeting attended by 12 people led to the development of a multiple criteria decision analysis (MCDA) model to summarize their views on the negative effects associated with various nicotine products; the results of this meeting were briefly presented in a research paper.
McKee and Capewell said one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive was said to have received funding from British American Tobacco in the past to conduct an independent study.
It has also validated BAT&#39;s public health accreditation in a sustainability report, it said.
They added that one of the 12 participants in the meeting declared funding received from an e-cigarette maker but not funding reported to have come from cigarette and tobacco company Philip Morris International.
The arguments on the basis of which the panel members were selected were not provided, but they include several well-known &quot;leaders&quot; in the production of electronic cigarettes, some of whom even declare in the paper the financing of the industry.
Other meeting participants are not known for tobacco control expertise.
The head of the tobacco control section of PHE also attended the meeting.
The research paper produced by the group &quot;convincingly disguises&quot; the fact that there is a lack of &quot;robust evidence that most products are harmful by most criteria,&quot; McKee and Capewell said.
However, the PHE report does not mention any of these links or limitations.
McKee and Capewell said PHE&#39;s claims that &quot;to date there is no evidence that e-cigarettes are a factor that encourages smoking among children or non-smokers&quot; are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of health at PHE, says it has responded to claims in the BMJ in the past.
He stated: &quot;E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking&quot;
One in two people who have smoked all their lives will die from this habit.
All the evidence suggests that the health risk of e-cigarettes is comparatively minor, but we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what is and what is not from the evidence, particularly given the high degree of public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Every year, around 80,000 people die from a smoking-related illness and the annual cost to the national health system of smoking is £2 billion.
By making clear the current evidence - that although e-cigarette use is not without risk, it is only a fraction of the harmful effect of smoking - we are fulfilling our national duty.
