So, if we look at this world, we have on the one hand skilled workers, which is stupid, and an audience that cannot listen, but must watch, which is also stupid&quot;, considered David Grimal.
The violinist says that this change in the way he makes music came as a result of &quot;musical disappointments&quot; in his career as a soloist.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise all over the world with different orchestras, to earn a lot of money and to bring money to the music industry as well.
10 years ago, when I was around 30 years old, I found this very depressing, because I no longer found creativity and human brotherhood in this system.
So, I didn&#39;t find any sense to continue on this path.
Thus I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This happened in 2004, and at that time no one did such a thing without a conductor: &quot;The musical world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects&quot;.
&quot;How do you imagine doing marketing with a collective of musicians in which there is no longer any ego?&quot; asks the artist.
David Grimal admits that Les Dissonaces represents &quot;a luxury&quot;, specifying that none of the musicians who are part of the orchestra depend on the success of this project to live.
In 10 years of the ensemble&#39;s existence, the lack of a conductor did not prove to be an obstacle in the musical act: &quot;Curiously, the more complex a repertoire we play, the simpler it seems, because all the musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not just in the role&quot;, says Grimal, adding that at the Sunday performance &quot;there were 74 conductors on stage&quot;.
In Grimal&#39;s opinion, the Enescu Festival is a &quot;very brave one&quot;, precisely because it also invited Les Dissonances: &quot;An extraordinary festival, where the biggest orchestras in the world are present and play 3 times a day, and in the middle of these orchestras you also invited this strange group&quot;.
In a temple of orchestral tradition, such as the Enescu Festival, there is a place and interest for something different, which breaks barriers.
Speaking about Enescu&#39;s work, the violinist admits that he feels the Romanian music of the famous Romanian composer, so that he did not need a special approach when he introduced works by Enescu into his repertoire.
Grimal notes that Enescu&#39;s music is very instinctive, but this happens when we talk about George Enescu and Romanian music, &quot;because there was also a George Enescu who made French music&quot;.
Grimal advocates for changing the way classical music education is done, considering that &quot;the profession of musician, as it is organized today, has a death knell&quot; and that &quot;the future of music is music itself&quot;.
We don&#39;t need to go around the world 5 times a year if it serves no purpose.
There were no world tours in Bach&#39;s time.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, organizing concerts, festivals, tours, releasing albums, they are all formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are done in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, it no longer has freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave the example of Romanian products before and after joining the European Union: &quot;In Romania, before entering the EU, you had good vegetables and meat&quot;.
To enter the EU you had to adopt sanitary laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
Production and agriculture end up at the service of supermarkets, as is also happening in France.
The same thing happens with music, it&#39;s the same logic.
Les Dissonances makes tomatoes that may not be very beautiful, but when we cut them they are real tomatoes.
In an ideal world, this music should come back to the center and the institutions and industries that manage this system understand that music doesn&#39;t need to be sold, it needs to be shared, and this can be done by starting with educational policy.
&quot;If we considered - as the Koreans, the Chinese, the Japanese do - that Western music is one of the most beautiful things of humanity, we would reintroduce its learning in school, we would reintroduce concerts on television and through this education there would be no need to we sell musical by-products&quot;, believes Grimal.
Certainly, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, this everywhere, it is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline if we compare a musician with a soldier, or if we train a musician who will play an instrument, being, above all, a musician.
We are talking about a completely different education, if we want to train a soldier (this education - ed.) it must be in one way, if we want to train a musician, it is completely different.
In your opinion, what is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?&quot;, asks the French artist smiling.
Grimal shows that, for artists, the reward of a different way of making music comes precisely from overcoming this &quot;soldier&quot; status, overcoming what &quot;they think are their limits&quot;: &quot;Musicians discover at a certain moment that they are not soldiers, and that&#39;s why they come out smiling after the concert&quot;.
David Grimal spoke about his musical project and his vision on music and on the artist during the &quot;Festival of Ideas&quot;, a discussion with the public organized within the International George Enescu Festival by the Aspen Romania Institute.
Profile David Grimal
After attending the Conservatoire National Superieur de Musique in Paris under Regis Pasquier, during which time he received advice and encouragement from renowned artists such as Schlomo Mintz and Isaac Stern, David Grimal studied for a year at the Ecole des Science Politiques from Paris before the meeting with Philippe Hirshhorn, who changed the course of his life.
David Grimal has an international career as a solo violinist, during which he has regularly given concerts over the last 20 years on the main classical music stages of the world and with prestigious orchestras such as the Orchester de Paris, Orchester Philharmonique de Radio France, Russian National Orchestra, Orchester National de Lyon, Chamber Orchestra of Europe, Berliner Symphoniker, New Japan Philharmonic, Orchester de l&#39;Opera de Lyon, Mozarteum Orchestra Salzburg, Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra and Sinfonia Varsovia, under conductors such as Christoph Eschenbach, Michel Plasson, Michael Schￃnwandt, Peter Csaba, Heinrich Schiff, Lawrence Foster, Emmanuel Krivine, Mikhail Pletnev, Rafael Fruￌhbeck de Burgos and Peter Eotvos, Andris Nelsons, Christian Arming.
He was the recipient of dedicated works from several composers, including Marc-Andre Dalbavie, Brice Pauset, Thierry Escaich, Jean-Francois Zygel, Alexander Gasparov, Victor Kissine, Fuminori Tanada, Richard Dubugnon, Ivan Fedele, Philippe Harrowing , Anders Hillborg, Oscar Bianchi, Guillaume Connesson and Frederic Verrieres.
Besides his career as a solo artist, David Grimal also wanted to explore more personal projects.
The freedom offered by the collaboration with Les Dissonances allowed him to develop his inner universe by venturing into repertoires that are not accessible to solo artists.
Along with Les Dissonances, he founded &quot;L&#39;Autre Saison&quot;, a series of concerts given for the benefit and together with the homeless at the Saint-Leu church, located in the heart of Paris.
Since 2008, David Grimal has been Artist in Residence at the Dijon Opera.
He teaches violin at the Musikhochschule in Saarbrücken, Germany.
He also holds many master classes and was a member of the jury of the Long-Thibaud International Competition in Paris in 2010.
He was awarded the Chevalier des Arts et des Lettres by the French Minister of Culture in 2008.
David Grimal plays on a Stradivarius, &quot;ex Roederer&quot; from 1710, but also on &quot;Don Quixote&quot;, a violin designed for him by the French luthier Jacques Fustier.
David Grimal was present on Sunday at this year&#39;s George Enescu International Festival together with the Les Dissonances Orchestra, with Debussy, Enescu and Beethoven in the program.
Les Dissonances took the stage again on Monday, this time with cellist Xavier Phillips in the foreground, and the program was composed by Schnittke, Enescu and Brahms.
