In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether the time has come to raise a key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank&#39;s boardroom, a mural of the United States will loom.
The map is meant to remind Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues that the nation&#39;s economic interests must come first.
The Central Bank has been given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the US and to maintain price stability.
But since the Great Depression, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And that third task could be the X-factor in an all-too-anticipated decision on Tuesday that will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be stripped of the unprecedented stimulus provided by near-term interest rates zero effective from the end of 2008.
Even though most data points to a strong growing economy, the recent jitters in global financial markets could spook Fed officials already wary of adding volatility by raising the benchmark federal funds rate — even by just a quarter of a percentage point .
&quot;Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and foremost things they&#39;ll be watching,&quot; said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co.
&quot;But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait,&quot; she said.
There is no consensus as to what decision the Fed will take, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg expected an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to hold off, with a key indicator showing the likelihood of a hike is just 30 percent.
That would indicate a bear market if the Fed raises interest rates, unless policymakers soften the blow by promising that it will be a long time before the next hike.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to 16,599.85.
The momentum was sparked by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep interest rates steady this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody&#39;s Capital Markets Research Group.
&quot;It would be surprising for the Fed to raise interest rates at this point,&quot; Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers were to do so, &quot;they would have to act deeply in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.&quot;
Other experts said a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed looked set to raise rates by 0.25 percent this month, the first small step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage earnings showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to miss the central bank&#39;s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply lower oil prices.
The economy &quot;can handle higher rates and needs them given the strain on the labor market,&quot; said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to falter later this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16 percent below a record high reached in May as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has pulled back somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market jitters add to the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
&quot;Without what happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be more bullish at the meeting,&quot; said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official. .
Now, he expects they&#39;ll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
&quot;There&#39;s a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to go by after the events in China,&quot; Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed&#39;s major interests, so it should practically not factor into its decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world&#39;s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The mere hint by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might “tape” its monetary expansion sent tremors through global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly twinned, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret world economy.
Its decision-making process is &quot;more art than science,&quot; said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that &quot;the Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic fundamentals.&quot;
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, the decision-making body that supported the rate hike, offered the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis affecting Asia prompted the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, &quot;despite the limited identifiable implications for US growth,&quot; Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should put financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England&#39;s interest rate-setting committee.
The last turbulent period is nowhere near that level, he said.
&quot;We certainly don&#39;t want to end up in a situation where we fear an interest rate hike because the markets are upset,&quot; said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has the dual mandate and no mention of financial stability, and until something changes about that, I don&#39;t think they should act prematurely.
