Weight-loss surgery may be helpful in mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still too early to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those who undergo nonsurgical treatments.
&quot;It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,&quot; said obesity surgery specialist Dr. Robin Blackstone, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss surgery, also called bariatric surgery, uses various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body&#39;s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of measurement of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
A BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery -- gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy -- in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes. in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who had surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of people who received non-surgical diabetes treatments remained almost the same at 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured in 36% and partially in 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1 percent and partially cured in only 2 percent of subjects.
In addition, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and &quot;bad&quot; LDL cholesterol &quot;were generally better in the surgery group,&quot; the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at around 8%.
But this improved &quot;glycemic control&quot; — reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels — did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), had greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. of 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) and showed a higher probability of complete diabetes remission (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a survival benefit or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die after 15 years compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study didn&#39;t show a survival benefit in patients who had the surgery, Blackstone said it&#39;s an optimistic look for people with a BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
&quot;That&#39;s where this paper is critical, because it says that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,&quot; without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when a patient&#39;s BMI reaches 27-30.
&quot;I think we&#39;re waiting too long to get people to take this seriously,&quot; she said.
I think once they&#39;ve accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it&#39;s extremely hard to get back to normal.
