On Wednesday, the government approved the &quot;National Immigration Strategy for the period 2015-2018&quot; and the &quot;Action Plan for the current year&quot;, documents considered to be &quot;another stage that Romania is going through in the efforts to modernize the management process of immigration on the national territory&quot;, according to a press release.
The cited source shows that the strategy aims at the efficient management of the immigration phenomenon, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect the policies established at the European level, adapted to national realities.
Considering the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are being considered for the unitary and coherent management of the situations determined by the possible appearance of an influx of illegal immigrants on the territory of Romania, generated by natural crisis situations political, social, economic or military.
&quot;The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but, at the same time, they will pay special attention to citizens from states with migration potential or that may harm national security&quot;, adds the mentioned source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including the maintenance of the conflict situation in Syria, the reactivation of the conflict in Iraq, the maintenance of an unstable situation in the areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), the perpetuation and increase in intensity of the Israeli armed conflict - Palestinian.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: the promotion of legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the stay of citizens of third countries on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improving the system national of asylum.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
Among them are: the facilitation of access to the territory of Romania for third-party citizens who meet the employment needs of the labor force, favoring the access of third-party citizens to higher education institutions in Romania for the fields and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciates that it represents &quot;a means by which concrete activities are established to lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon&quot;.
Romania, in a European top regarding the labor market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the largest increase in the total cost of labor among the member states of the European Union, in the second quarter of the year, compared to the same period in 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Office for Statistics (Eurostat). .
The index refers to employers&#39; personnel expenses.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total labor cost rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, in the third place in the EU for the increase in labor costs
The largest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU states where the hourly labor cost fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The increase in labor costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in the hourly cost of labor in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania registered an advance of 5.8% of the hourly labor cost.
