In the refugee crisis, Romania has so far played as a small country.
It&#39;s a legitimate strategy, but after that you can&#39;t ask to be treated as the seventh EU country.
Big countries come up with solutions for the entire EU, says Cristian Ghinea, member of the board of directors of the Romanian Center for European Policies.
In an interview given to Ziare.com, Cristian Ghinea showed that Europe cannot be transformed into a fortress, and purely police means will not work in this crisis: &quot;Maybe we have doubts about the quality of the values these people bring&quot; .
But there are masses who have started and we cannot turn back history.
Migration is a reality to which we must adapt as best as possible and adapt them to us.
In Cristian Ghinea&#39;s opinion, we are in an extremely emotional moment, in which politicians feel the need to show their muscles.
After he passes, the Europeans will not be willing to give up free movement, but the rules in the Schengen area must be changed: &quot;Schengen is now like an animal created in another era and which was not adapted for the current situation&quot;.
Where are we in the refugee crisis after this JAI council which, in fact, did not solve anything?
It is clear that the EC president, in agreement with Donald Tusk, did not want to force a vote in the council.
All forecasts said that he would have had the necessary votes.
Before the Treaty of Lisbon, the principle of unanimity was applied in the JHA and any state could block any decision.
That is why things were very little integrated in the field of justice and internal affairs.
After Lisbon, the normal procedure is applied, in which the EC has the initiative, and the council approves it with the vote of 55% of the states, i.e. 16, representing 65% of the EU population.
The calculations said that the votes were there.
But they did not want to go forward.
Because it is a sensitive matter, rejection reactions appeared even in Germany against Chancellor Merkel&#39;s opening policy and they did not want it to appear in many countries as a reaction of the type &quot;EU is sending migrants on our heads&quot;.
So they postponed it, but the problem remains because, obviously, this wave creates a huge problem for Schengen governance and we will probably witness big changes there in the next period.
So the mandatory quotas were not really eliminated, but the subject was just left to cool down?
Yes, on the other hand, there is talk of a greater involvement of the Frontex agency in the management of the external borders, which means a change from the individual responsibility of the members who are at the external Schengen border to the responsibility of the community agencies.
Greece&#39;s border with Turkey is also Germany&#39;s border with Turkey, de facto, and this wave of migrants gave the limits of the old Schengen system.
Perhaps the Dublin principle will be abandoned, according to which migrants are the responsibility of the state they enter for the first time, because it is not sustainable.
If Greece capsizes, you cannot forever say that it is Greece&#39;s fault.
The problem is common.
Precisely because the problem is common, is a solution possible without a precise, perhaps even mandatory, mechanism for sharing the reception effort?
No one knows exactly how the mandatory quotas will work, if they will be reached.
Because there remains a problem: what do you do with a man who doesn&#39;t want to come to Romania or Portugal, but to Sweden or Germany?
I don&#39;t think that the European states will start taking migrants: you go to country X or country Y.
We will probably reach some unique filtering centers, in Greece or Turkey, where asylum applications will be processed.
We are working on solutions like this.
But the problem does not have a simple solution.
There are countries that have decades of experience in trying to integrate migrants, there are countries without any experience, like Romania, where the problem of migrants will increase the xenophobic trend.
It is certain that we are talking about millions of people who are in Turkey, in Lebanon, in Jordan, who are staying in precarious camps and who have just started to leave for Europe.
An estimate says that only 10% managed to leave, it&#39;s hard to cross the Mediterranean in winter, but next year we expect an even bigger wave.
What do we do with these people?
My prediction is that we will get used to this problem, we will no longer look at it so catastrophically from a media point of view.
Talk about countries with less or more experience.
Do you think there is any place where the integration of large groups from a non-European culture has really succeeded?
I look at the Maghrebians in France, at the Turks in Germany, they are still enclaved.
I would not go for radical statements.
Of course, their integration is more difficult than in the case of other waves of migration, but that does not mean that they do not integrate at all.
It remained an unintegrated part that creates major social problems in France, in Germany, in Great Britain.
But purely police means will not work.
To create a fortress Europe is illusory.
We must go to the mechanisms of integration in European societies.
There were some mistakes here.
We have to be more demanding.
Let&#39;s ask these people to learn the language, to try to take over the values, not to stay with one foot in Europe and one in their country of origin, bringing the rest of their family including through marriages of convenience.
However, the imminent problem of these people must be separated from the long-term problem of their integration.
If others have failed in long-term integration, it does not mean that we have to watch them drown in the Mediterranean.
Maybe we have doubts about the quality of the values that these people bring.
And if there will be an intervention in Syria, which I do not believe, it does not mean that the country will be restored overnight and you can take them back.
Until solutions appear, we see fortresses within Europe.
Borders have been closed, walls are being erected, border controls are being reintroduced in the Schengen area.
Is the European project in danger?
The European project as such no, the Schengen space as it was built, yes.
It was built quite minimally and arranging the rules so that the pressure was too great on the countries where these migrants set foot for the first time.
I mean, we move freely here and there, but everyone has their own problems.
In the face of such a wave, this cannot be done, because some countries cannot cope.
When there are such waves of emotion, politicians want to show that they are doing something, but in the long term, not much changes.
After the attacks in France, we do not have much more draconian anti-terrorist legislation in the EU than we had last year.
It&#39;s a wave of public emotion that sets in in both directions.
And it is so unstable from one week to the next that you cannot make decisions based on it.
We have a lot of talk, many bellicose statements from politicians at home under pressure to be virile.
And, then, you have the dramatic case of the drowned child in Turkey and public opinion gets emotional.
After the public emotion passes, we will return to the reasons why we created this space, this freedom of movement that is not only for people, but also for goods.
This is the real single European market.
And I don&#39;t think the Europeans will give up this principle of freedom of movement.
That there will be other rules is something else.
Schengen is now like an animal created in another era and which was not adapted for the current situation.
How has Romania played so far in this crisis?
Like a small country, which thinks that if it pulls the cap over its eyes and plugs its ears, the theme disappears.
Faced with the reality of waves of migrants, you can choose to be part of the solution or say that it is not your small country&#39;s problem.
That&#39;s what we did, it&#39;s a legitimate strategy, but after that you can&#39;t ask to be treated as the seventh EU country.
You are not, you do not play at the level of a large country.
Big countries come up with solutions for the entire EU, good or bad, we are not discussing their quality now.
As Poland did.
On the other hand, the effect of this crisis is that Romanians&#39; appetite for Schengen will decrease a lot.
President Iohannis says that maybe it&#39;s good that I didn&#39;t enter already.
So we move from the desperation of entry to a more pragmatic position, but the objective remains.
There is of course a risk if Romania and Bulgaria enter Schengen that migrants will see us as an alternative route.
Which does not mean that it is a reason not to enter Schengen, but to be more pragmatic.
Romania will be part of Schengen, and Schengen will exist, but transformed in the sense that the external borders will become a common responsibility, there will be unique rules for accepting migrants, unique rules for deportation for those who do not receive asylum, unique rules for countries considered safe.
