EXCLUSIVE: A date that breaks your heart.
At 20, he received a brave gift: his biological parents
Lost in the hospital under unclear circumstances, in the fog of the 90s, when she was only two months old, tiny, sick and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years when adoption was loosely regulated, a young Ieșeancă, now a blonde and beautiful girl, was reunited the day before yesterday in Iasi with her biological parents from a village in the county, after almost two decades in which no one knew anything about the others.
Crina will turn 20 these days, and her adoptive parents from Palermo thought of giving their beloved daughter an amazing and brave gift: a visit to Romania, to Iași, to get to know her unclear past.
&quot;Ziarul de Iași&quot;, which witnessed the efforts to find the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, witnessed these encounters that practically break your heart.
The reporting of the reporters, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are downright moving and overwhelming.
Crina&#39;s story begins 20 years ago in the town of Ruginoasa, Iasi, when she was only two months old.
Then, due to a health problem, the girl had to be hospitalized in the city.
At home, there began to be misunderstandings between the parents, and the mother had to leave the residence.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away from home.
He stopped the girl, and I haven&#39;t heard from her since.
&quot;When I found out that she was in the hospital, it was too late,&quot; recalls Alina, the girl&#39;s biological mother, sorrowfully.
Crina was hospitalized together with her grandmother at the municipal hospital in Pașcani, and also then the girl&#39;s father, Costică Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman county.
Their lives would be separated for good.
They never found Crina at the hospital
After hospitalization, Crina&#39;s father went to work in another locality, and returned six months later.
In the meantime, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iași, and the father, when he returned, could not find her.
I think it had been almost nine months since the girl had been in the hospital.
&quot;She would have thought she was abandoned,&quot; says a niece of the family.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of the doctors.
Because no one was interested in the fate of the child during all this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection in Iași, which then gave her for care to the Placement Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more loosely regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center she was found by the Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but could not.
They immediately fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after some time she would permanently move with them to Italy.
The little girl was already almost two years old, while the adoption formalities lasted.
When I saw Crina, I felt like she was our girl.
&quot;As if my wife had given her life,&quot; Salvadore, the adoptive father, tells us with a smile, while holding the girl&#39;s frail hand in his palm.
In the country, Crina&#39;s parents, Alina and Costică, continued their search separately, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but he did not receive any answer where his child could be.
The police then told her that she might be dead, but in Iași the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the Court that she was away in Italy, in Palermo.
And I didn&#39;t have the conditions to look for it.
We prayed to God that it would be okay.
I thought about her all the years that passed, but there were no possibilities to walk, to find her.
&quot;It&#39;s hard&quot;, Crina&#39;s biological mother tells us with tears in her eyes.
But, even if the years have passed, the parents from Ruginoasa have not been forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she comes from and that her past connects her to Romania.
I was little when I found out.
I think I was five or six years old.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
&quot;I wanted to meet my parents from Romania&quot;, confesses Crina excitedly.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March of this year, chief commissioner Romică Ichim, director of the Iași Regional Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling Center, was contacted by an acquaintance from Italy, who explained Salvadore&#39;s desire to find Crina&#39;s biological family.
And the searches started only from a name.
After the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I had only received a name, Balcan Costică, then the locality, Ruginoasa.
Shortly after, I had an activity with the town hall there, and I was able to ask if the given name existed in the locality.
Then they gave me some directions, only that the person they found was not the one they were looking for.
&quot;In the end, it took about a month to find the girl&#39;s biological father,&quot; explains chief commissioner Romică Ichim.
In total, it took the authorities more than three months to find Costică and Alina, especially since each lived in a different locality.
We started the steps somewhere in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of the biological parents and the discussions.
&quot;Then we decided that a first meeting should take place in September&quot;, Romică Ichim added.
Last weekend, Alina and Costică saw their lost girl for the first time in the corridors of the hospital in Iasi, 20 years ago.
The father, moved, could hardly control his tears, and his hands were constantly shaking.
He barely exchanged a few words with those around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn&#39;t even sleep.
He was still excited, shaking.
&quot;To see your child after so many years is something&quot;, a granddaughter tells us, she also came with Costică from Ruginoasa.
Crina&#39;s meeting with her mother and biological brother
In discussions with his daughter, who is going to study at a well-rated university in Italy, Costică Balcan told her, among other things, that if she ever wants to return to his village, to come quietly: he can give her some sheep, goats , to find a boy from the village and start a household.
The mother is also emotional, she cries, and she can hardly believe that something like this could happen to her.
I&#39;m very nervous.
I didn&#39;t think something like this could happen.
I saw cases like this on TV, I kept thinking about it all these years, I hoped, but I didn&#39;t think that I could be like that too.
There are very big emotions.
If you could forgive me.
I hope to visit in the future.
&quot;I hope we can keep a connection&quot;, says Alina, Crina&#39;s mother, with big tears on her cheeks, while holding a napkin tightly in her hand.
In it she still hides her tears, of happiness, because in a short time she will see her girl after such a bitter time.
On the other hand, Crina, who will turn 20 in just a few days this month, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn&#39;t know what to expect, but she has a vague idea of her biological parents.
He thinks they are young, but now before the meeting he tries to collect his thoughts, because he has a lot to say, but nothing to complain about.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
But my parents are ultimately the ones who raised me.
It will be a beautiful meeting, a wonderful experience.
&quot;I hope to have a nice memory with them, because now there are so many things to say&quot;, confesses Crina.
The first family reunion in Iasi
In Piata Unirii, under the early autumn sky, the family from Ruginoasa reunites their destiny with their girl from Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, she finished high school, according to the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costică, her biological parents.
Borders or countries no longer separate them, but only a barrier: that of language.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian restaurant owner in the center of Iași, they passed easily.
Those who managed to make this meeting possible say that it is the first event of this kind done, and that, in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It is the first organized event of this kind, with such an emotional charge, and I am glad that it was a success.
We, at the Center, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with drug users, drug addicts.
But we try to give something back to society.
&quot;If I will be asked again for such an event, I will do it with great pleasure,&quot; says smiling Romică Ichim, the director of the Iași Regional Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling Center.
Behind him, the Balkan family, with Crina in the middle, walks away telling a story.
It&#39;s understandable: they have a lot to say to each other.
