The great sculptor had a big dream: to be somebody, to become famous, to be heard about all over the world.
But behind his fame is something almost forgotten today, when millions of success stories are delivered to us, recipes for success in life.
That thing also has a name.
It&#39;s called &quot;toil&quot;.
What to write about Constantin Brâncusi?
What more is there to say, really?
His figure appeared on banknotes.
And, recently, a well-known Romanian bank hired an actor to play him in an advertising clip.
Brâncusi produces and delivers money almost 60 years after he is no longer with us.
In Romania, there are hundreds of streets and boulevards that bear his name.
Incidentally, even the author of this text lives on one of these streets.
And, when he goes outside with the child, he hears the following instructions: &quot;Let&#39;s go to the park, to Brâncusi&quot;.
The country is studded with his statues.
There are few Romanian personalities whose works are known to so many people, from children to the elderly.
Brâncusi&#39;s infiltration capacity is huge.
Even the communists did not manage to extirpate him from Romania&#39;s memory and culture.
His quotes litter the internet today, receiving hundreds of thousands of likes and shares.
And, then, again, what would be left to say, to write about this man?
Seen from the pile of books and articles that try to reconstruct his destiny, Brâncusi&#39;s life seems almost fantastic, totally improbable.
You know, there are those people who tell you that unless you were lucky enough to be born in a big city and into a somewhat wealthy family, your chances of success in life are almost nil.
Brâncusi&#39;s life is the perfect counterexample.
And maybe there&#39;s a key here.
Perhaps this is where the following text should begin.
With a sentence, however detestable they may be.
Forget the cretinous success stories that are delivered to you daily in newspapers and on television.
Look carefully at the figure of this man.
Do you want to know how he succeeded in life, how, today, the entire world has heard of him?
It&#39;s simple.
He worked his whole life to be somebody.
That&#39;s what he did.
Constantin Brâncuși was born on February 19, 1876, in Hobita, a small village in Peștişani commune, Gorj county, at the foot of the Carpathians.
He is the fifth child of Maria and Radu Nicolae Brâncusi.
Although he came from a wealthy peasant family, Brâncusi led a modest life, but one from which he would gather the landmarks that would guide his later artistic vision.
Remembering his childhood and the places where he grew up, the artist would confess, in a meeting with Petre Țuțea, from Paris, in 1933: &quot;Back then life was beautiful and harmonious&quot;.
For millennia, people happily lived a patriarchal life.
Everything passed quietly from one season to another.
And do you know why things have changed?
The civilization of the big city has reached us.
However, Brâncusi&#39;s childhood was far from idyllic.
One of the moments spent in these first years of life is highly suggestive of the combination of purity and violence that characterized the future sculptor&#39;s years spent in his hometown.
The moment is reproduced in the work &quot;Brâncusi. A biography&quot;, written by Alexandru Buican.
In 1879, Constantin Brâncusi was 3 years old.
In the fall of that year, when the brandy was being made &quot;in the cauldron&quot;, watching those tasting the liquid to see if the process was going as it should, Brâncuși caught a moment of general inattention.
He fills the palm of his hand with brandy and drinks breathlessly.
He falls asleep almost instantly.
The first people notice only after a few minutes.
The mother panics, then hysterics, believing her son is dead.
In the evening, when the father, Radu, returns from the vineyard accompanied by fiddlers, he sees from afar the desperate signs of those who are waiting for him with their hearts in their mouths.
The party immediately turns to mourning.
The father is already thinking about the burial.
However, someone finds it good to call Baba Brândușa, doftoroaia and servant of the Brâncuși.
Brânduša checks the child&#39;s breathing, then puts horse dung, collected nearby, under his nose.
The child sneezes loudly.
The world applauds.
While the boy is left to sleep off his drunkenness, out of joy, the party with the fiddlers continues with even more force.
The next day, father and son meet in the orchard.
Radu Brâncusi asks Constantin to gather some sticks and bring them to him.
The father places his child upside down and, with the sticks brought by the boy, beats him to make him remember.
And, while feeling the sting of the blows, little Brâncusi has the revelation that the world can be seen from another perspective and that things around can appear upside down.
Especially the position of the sun, different from the well-known one, makes him wonder, as he would admit in his old age, if the star itself was not participating in his disturbance.
Was the sun as troubled as his father by what had happened to him?
